animal.description:
Autumn! She is a beautiful and sweet Doberman, we guess her to be 1-2 years old and she is around 65 lbs. She is a medium/high energy dog that needs regular exercise.

Please read all about Autumn (below) and if you feel you are a good match for her and want to meet her, please complete an application found on our website, we will be adopting Autumn into the Portland area only.
www.mywayhomedogrescue.org

This sweet girl is smart, sweet, playful, alert, excitable, and a true velcro dog that wants to be by you. She does pretty well on leash, she is crate trained (not a fan but will crate-up) and house trained (when offered to go outside often). 

This sweet girl had a surprise when she came into our rescue and one sweet puppy was born a couple weeks after arriving to Oregon. Her puppy has been weaned, is adopted and now it is Autumn’s turn. 

Autumn has a head tilt that is more noticeable when she is nervous and nearly imperceptible when she is relaxed. She does not seem to exhibit any neurological concerns and there do not appear to be any major medical concerns, but she may have a lifelong tendency to tilt her head (which only adds to her sweet and silly disposition).

Autumn’s ideal home has a securely fenced yard, people who are home most of the time, provides lots of belly rubs, occasional peanut butter, a comfy bed (or her preference your bed or couch), regular exercise, and play time with squeaky toys and bones. Autumn will do best with a dog to hang with, a dog that is confident and calm with good behaviors for her to follow. Her favorite game with her dog friends is chase!

Autumn is still young and has been through quite a bit, though she still remains sweet and loving. She will benefit from a dog experienced home willing to continue her training. She has high prey drive so no cats for her! She loves to jump so no children.

Autumn has had her vaccinations, heart wormed tested, has been spayed, de-wormed, had flea treatment, and is microchipped. Her adoption fee is $350.

animal.description:
Meet handsome Jasper, just a pup at 4-5 months old and 30 lbs. He is so cute! He is the coolest mix of 5 breeds! 33% staffordshire terrier, 29% labrador, 27% australian cattle dog, 8% chihuahua!, and 3% miniature american shepherd.

He is a kind boy and young enough to have the exact right start in life, with training being number one on the list - for him and for you!

Jasper likes dogs and cats, but kids make him really nervous, so a sans-child home will do him well. Another dog in the home will give him confidence. Being an only dog will not help him thrive.

He is smart, knows how to leash walk, learning commands. He loves to go hiking, too.

Jasper is shy at first, not quite sure of his place in the world. After he warms up he is ok. He startles easily as well.

We will want to work with him on meeting strangers as it makes him nervous. We have great tools that his foster mom is practicing and will be passed on to you.

He is so sweet, loves his toys, loves to play, and run around in the yard. He is prone to jumping up to say hi and that is being worked on. He loves to cuddle, loves it!

He is now updated on all shots, neutered, and will be chipped. His adoption fee is $495.

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
These sweet babies were picked up this weekend. They were found dumped and poor little Peavey was injured. Peavey’s leg was swollen and he couldn’t use it. Thankfully, we had a foster step up and were able to get them seen and Peavey is now healing great and using his leg. We are unsure if their mix. Probably some lab in there. Maybe some terrier. They will be medium sized as adults we believe. They are 6-8 weeks and around 5lbs. They are super sweet and playful. Great with all animals and people. They truly are great for pretty much any family. They will be ready for adoption on 2/10 after their second vaccines and they are altered. 

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
We all fell in love with this chunky little boy the minute he walked into our shelter.  Stubby is a male Corgi/Golden Retriever mix puppy and simply adorable!  He has a fluffy black and tan coat and is super soft and cuddly.  Stubby is quite unusual looking with his short stocky legs.  He’s what you call a “low-rider”.  At five months old, he weighs thirty pounds and will be a medium sized dog when full grown.  Stubby is very affectionate and loves to give kisses.  This boy will make a fabulous family pet for anyone with time to train a puppy.  He is working on his house manners and will need a fenced in yard.  Stubby is a loving playful pup and wonderful with children.  He has quite the toy collection and doesn’t mind sharing.  He’s great with other dogs and would love to have a playmate.  Stubby is an affectionate puppy that will make a wonderful addition to your family.  Get your application in quickly because this pup is sure to be popular.  

To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

animal.description:
Hey Hey, my name is Oslo! I'm about 6 months old and 40 pounds, part terrier, part pointer, and all cute and soft! I am curious, and silly and affectionate. I'm still a puppy so still working on my crate and house training, but I learn quickly and am eager to please. My foster mama takes me to work with her and I do so well there as long as I have a few toys and chewies to keep me busy. I love other dogs and would really love to live with a doggie friend! I'm also very friendly and outgoing with people! I'm looking for a person/family who is home a lot and will continue my training and socialization with lots of love and consistency- I promise to be the best boy! 

Due to the current events, the rescue is not able to host adoption events.  Please fill out an application and we will conduct phone interviews and set up outdoor meet and greets! www.thegooddogrescue.org

My adoption fee is $300 and I am neutered, microchipped and up to date on vaccinations

animal.description:
Just look at that face. Ace will steal your heart once you look into his eyes. Ace is about 10 months old and weights about 47 lbs. He's ready for an active person to swoop in and adopt him. He is equal part sweetness and energy. 

Ace enjoys long walks and even likes rainy days. He will sometime bring his tennis ball or squeaky toy along on his walks and just strut along. Playing ball is one of his favorite past times. 

Ace does well on leash but if he sees a bird or squirrel he gets super excited. We feel Ace could use some basic leash training along with furthering his response to sit, stay, down and wait. He's very treat and toy motivated so that makes training easier.

Ace loves other dogs and is happy and wiggly with children. He likes them so much and he jumps when excited so he'd do best with children 8 and older. 

If you're interested in Ace click "Ask About Ace". This will generate an email inquiry to us and we'll respond back.

animal.description:
Valerie is a female, approximately two years old & about 45 lbs, found at an abandoned house. She is a very sweet girl though quite shy at first. She needs a lot of leash work but loves people and has tremendous potential to be a most awesome dog indeed!
DOG ADOPTION FEE is $100. This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more. (If a dog is sponsored or has a waived or lower fee, that info will be provided at the point of adoption to the approved adopter).
The first step is to our Adoption Application here: https://elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html .

animal.description:
www.TheLastResortRescue.com PLEASE NOTE: IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS PET THE FIRST STEP IS TO FILL OUT OUR ADOPTION APPLICATION AVAILABLE AT THELASTRESORTRESCUE.COM. If you have a question or inquiry please email us at tlrapplications@gmail.com
They say a picture is worth a thousand words.... well, a thousand more have been shouted.Misty was surrendered (yes, she had a 'home') in this condition. On a Friday. Less than 2 hours before animal control closed. Can you imagine how itchy she is? How painful it is to have your nails growing into the pads of her paws?Can you imagine at 10 years old being dumped at animal control???Why? Probably because she couldn't stop itching.... you know what would have stopped this? A simple pill. Once a month. What $10/ month??We immediately sprung Misty from the shelter amd she is currently receiving vet care at our partner ani.al hospital. She is already feeling SOO much better!!! ( see before/after pics)

Once she's clear for travel, Misty will travel north to her waiting foster in NJ who is our 'senior home' for our elderly rescues.
Once we evaluate her specific needs we will consider her availability for adoption.
Stay tuned.

animal.description:
Lady is the total package.  She is great in the house, she has herding behavior which is very quiet and soft, she never barks, she gets along with all of the other dogs, no issues whatsoever!  How can this dog be homeless?!  lady has a bobbed tail and the most beautiful masked face.  She has great recall and great manners.  She loves nothing more than a wide open field to run in big circles and try to get someone to chase her.  This heeler is such a smart girl, easy to love and ready to find her forever home.  She will let you know she is ready for playtime by nibbling on your toes !  Text us or call at 812-267-2814 and let us send you our adoption application.

Our adoption fee is a $180 non-refundable donation which includes:

Spay/Neuter
Rabies Vaccination

6-Way Vaccination
Heartworm Testing and Treatment if necessary
Worming 
Socialization with other dogs 
History of Origin of your new pet, complete medical history and veterinary contacts
Dedicated support after Adoption
Lifelong Safety Net for your Pet
Tips for your individual dog for a successful adoption and transition
   
We do not adopt out any dog as housebroken. Housebreaking your new pet is an important part of the bonding process and is a necessary commitment for a successful transition. Those first few weeks in your  home are when your new dog learns to trust and respect you, as his person. When adopting make sure you have thought out a potty training routine ahead of time, before bringing a new dog into your home.   We do reserve the right to inspect the home to ensure there will not be any conflicts or issues that could result in an unsuccessful introduction to the family.  In addition you may rest assured that every dog  offered to the public for adoption by All American Dawgs has been handled and under direct guidance of our personnel for no less than 30 days.  This time period is necessary to assess each pet, individually, for health issues and individual behavior  before they go to new homes.  Each and every dog, during this period, will get regular exercise via pack walks through the countryside and regular direction in  basic manners while  learning extremely necessary socialization skills.  Our goal is to bridge committed adopters to good minded companions and this is accomplished by helping rescue dogs learn the basic skills necessary for that next step, your family. 

Adopters must meet and spend time with their newly adopted dog via a scheduled Meet and Greet here at All American Dawgs in Rockport, Indiana.  We do not ship our dogs under any circumstances as they are members of our family and their safety is    Priority # 1.

Please visit our FaceBook site at https://www.facebook.com/AADawgs for even more albums and information of our adoptable dogs.  Give us a like and enjoy the updates of our friends and adopters.  The happiness and satisfaction of our adopters is of utmost importance as our adoptive families become part of the A. A. D. family.

If you see a dog that you would like to get to know a little better please email us at: 
AllAmericanDawgs@gmail.com or call at 812-267-2814 to receive an adoption
application to complete.  Once the application has been processed by All American Dawgs (usually within 24-48 hours) we will call you to set up a meet and greet day that is most convenient to your family.

Anyone that wishes to meet a particular dog must complete our application process first.  We do not have an open to the public facility and the best way to reach us is via email  at  AllAmericanDawgs@gmail. com or text at 812-267-2814.  Please also enjoy additional pictures under photos on our FaceBook site  https://www.facebook.com/AADawgs

animal.description:
This sweet boy is Dylan.  He is a 14 week old Bernese Mountain Dog/Shepherd mix who weighs 30 lbs but will be about 80 lbs full grown.  Dylan was rescued from a rural shelter where he broke with parvo.  He was treated and is now happy and healthy.  

Dylan is a very sweet and goofy boy.  He loves attention from his people and would be happy to follow them around and lay near them.  He is a pretty happy go lucky boy who is just a total sweetheart.  Dylan lives with other dogs and does well with them.  

Dylan would like a home where he is treated like a member of the family.  He just wants a home where they can spend a lot of time with him.  I am sure he would love an active family to keep him busy but also want to lay around the house with him.  

Dylan is working on house training.  He does pretty well using potty pads for the time being and knows to potty when he goes outside but he is just too young to fully hold his bladder so he will need continued training and patience.   

Dylan is neutered, microchipped, and current on his vaccines.  His adoption fee is $175.

If you would like to adopt Dylan and make him a part of your family, please contact ForeverYoursOKC@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Please call the shelter 516-869-6311 during working hours (Mon. to Fri. 9AM-4PM; Sat. 10-4PM) for more information about Vanessa, the adoption process at the shelter and to confirm availability.  Please go to www.theshelterconnection.com or to the shelter page on Petfinder for more information about and directions to the shelter.
Vanessa is a beautiful  3 year old husky mix that was pulled by us from an overcrowded shelter in Georgia. Because she is heartworm positive, a common mosquito borne illness in the south, her chances of being adopted were slim. Heartworm is curable, but can be a lengthy process. Rather than have her reside at the shelter for the entire duration of the treatment, we are seeking an adoptive family that will work with us on keeping up with her treatment. The Shelter Connection’s Mend-A-Paw fund will fully cover the cost of all heartworm related treatments, but any adoptive family must be willing and able to bring her either here or to our vet of choice for heartworm appointments. Vanessa will also require low activity throughout the duration of the treatment.
Vanessa is a sweet, medium energy girl that lives for belly rubs, but is cautious when meeting new people at first. She would do best in a dog experienced home without young children. Because of Vanessa’s medical condition we are seeking a family for her through an application process. If you would like to submit an application for Vanessa, please email us at animalshelter@northhempsteadny.gov

Hi there! I am a lovable little puppy! Even though I am cute as a button I will take some work as I adjust into my new home. Don't get me wrong, we will have a lot of fun in the meantime but I will need time to understand what's expected of me. I will need help on all those fun puppy things like house training and basic obedience. I want to learn everything I possibly can. I am pretty excited about life and doing new things! My goal is to be your lifelong companion and I should learn quickly with praise, treats and little patience. I'd really love for us to get enrolled in training classes, after all school is the best way to get us both educated on what it takes to raise a puppy! It will be fun to watch me as I'm learning, after all puppies can be pretty silly. If you're ready to take on all the fun and companionship, come on out to Wayside Waifs today!

animal.description:
Adopt Lola! 5y, Chihuahua , 9 lbs, SF, crate trained, shots.  ADULTS-ONLY HOMEOWNERS WITH SECURED YARD PREFERRED. Apply KenMarRescue.org

FAVORITE FOOD: What you’re eating 
FAVORITE PASTTIME: Sunbathing
PET PEEVE: Wind

I’m Lola! 

My parent died and left no provisions in their trust for me or my canine siblings. 

So my owner’s HUMAN (not humane) DAUGHTER decided to dump all of us at a shelter and call it a day. 

Yep, she couldn’t be done with us soon enough, her dead parent’s fur-kids.

I am not housebroken to your floorplan.

I am not a circus dog that knows tricks.

So don’t bother to ask.

I am a little girl, alone.

Depending on the kindness of strangers.

I went from one day sleeping inside a warm home to the next sleeping outside in a kennel with other dogs on the cement floor.

I wonder how you would survive.

If you have a large space in your heart and a small place in your home to give me the PATIENCE I am going to need to get over this trauma, I welcome you in my heart.

If you are new to pet parenting, I am not the dog for you.

If you have toddlers or smaller aged kids, don’t apply.

If your kids are mean, ditto.

I have been spayed recently so cannot undergo anesthesia again (it would be hard on my heart) for at least 6-12 months. I am in need of a dental cleaning, just so you know.

My “cherry eye,” doesn’t bother me but if it bothers you, you may want to have your vet look at it and tuck it in once you adopt me.

I am here on this match site to find a forever family that is willing to commit to me for all of my life.

Xo,
Lola

***

I love people; especially ones that give me massages, real steak or hamburger pieces as treats, and people that let me snooze in the sun. I have a favorite spot, right behind my ears, that I like to get rubbed. When that happens, I make a funny sound, because it feels so good! I get along with the dogs and people I have met at my foster parents’ house. They don’t have small children or cats which suits me fine since I am more inclined to want to be around adults anyway.  What can I say, I love the one on one attention! I enjoy car rides, new adventures & playing. I need a house full of soft beds, snuggles, and yummy treats.

If you can give me a home with a secured yard, playtime with you, keep my mind stimulated by teaching me new things and incorporating me into your daily routine, including two walks a day, then you can give me a miracle.

Adults only HOMEOWNERS preferred (gentle older teens ok) with secured yard in the So Cal area please. 

Please apply online at KenMarRescue.org

You too can help save a dog's life!
Can’t adopt? Want to help? Sponsor me!
- A small amount can mean the difference between a vaccine and a microchip.
- A larger amount could provide sterilization to "one more" needy orphan or help us bail him or her out before being put to sleep.
- An even larger donation could cover the food and medical for one or more orphans for an entire year or help cover the vet expenses on expensive surgeries for "special needs" orphans suffering from neglect, cruelty or accidental injury.

You can make a donation to Ken-Mar Rescue through Paypal, its safe, secure and easy. All donations are tax deductible and 100% of your donation goes directly towards the care of animals in need. For more information on how to become a life-saver and to join our Guardian Angel Program please go to KenMarRescue.org

animal.description:
Adrienne is a female, about eight months old as of late Jan, about 45 lbs, came to us as a stray no one ever came for. She is a very sweet girl, loves tummy rubs and stuffed toys. NOT good with cats though.
DOG ADOPTION FEE is $100. This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more. (If a dog is sponsored or has a waived or lower fee, that info will be provided at the point of adoption to the approved adopter).
The first step is to our Adoption Application here: https://elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html .
IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
To learn more about us, visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org; Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Bronco arrived at PRBJ because his time was up at the kill shelter he was staying at. They reached out to us for help and luckily we had one more spot open in the kennel. Bronco seems like a sweet and gentle boy. We will update his page with more information after we have had him for a couple of days.
Bronco is Heartworm Positive but please do not let this deter you from adopting this great dog. PRBJ practices the 'slow kill' method for heartowrms and we have found it to be very successful. The infected dogs take a strong antibiotic for 30 days (if you adopt durring that time we will supply it for you) and then all they need is their regular monthly heartworm preventitive.

****PROTOCOLE COVID-19****

NOTRE REFUGE RESTE FERMÉ AU PUBLIC. LES ADOPTIONS SERONT GÉRÉES SUR RENDEZ-VOUS UNIQUEMENT LES SAMEDIS.  MERCI 

Hatfield et Marcus...un duo à adopter. Chacun se complète et se respecte.
Hatfield, mâle Coonhound croisé né le 27 mars 2018. Propre, affectueux, énergique.
Marcus, mâle Beagle croisé né le 2 avril 2019. Propre, énergique, vocal, joueur.

Maison et cour clôturée nécessaires. 
Ces deux chiens aiment travailler physiquement et mentalement. Des activités quotidiennes devront donc être prévues ( marches en laisse, jeux de recherche de nourriture, jeux de résolution de problèmes, etc) afin de les stimuler et canaliser leur énergie.
On recherche des gens très actifs, avec expérience de la race, très présents, milieu non urbain, pas d’autres animaux, ni enfants ni adolescents.

Dans l’espace prévu pour les commentaires, veuillez s’il vous plaît nous indiquer votre profil d’adoptant, à savoir tous les renseignements pertinents à votre sujet afin de constater si le chien pourrait être un bon match pour vous. Ainsi, votre expérience avec les chiens, si vous vivez en appartement ou maison, si votre cour est clôturée, les membres de votre famille, si vous avez d’autres animaux...Indiquez bien votre numéro de téléphone. 

SVP ne pas appeler le refuge pour les informations concernant nos animaux en adoption. Merci

Seules les demandes d’adoption retenues recevront un retour de courriel ou un appel téléphonique. 

Frais d’adoption: 340$, incluant la stérilisation, la vaccination et les vermifuges. Il n’y a pas de taxes. 

NOTE: il n’y a pas d’adoption avec enfants de 10 ans et moins



**** COVID-19 PROTOCOL****

OUR SHELTER REMAINS CLOSED TO THE PUBLIC.  ADOPTIONS WILL BE MANAGED BY APPOINTMENT ONLY ON SATURDAYS. THANK YOU !

Hatfield and Marcus...a duo to adopt. Each one completes and respects the other.
Hatfield, male Coonhound mix born March 27, 2018. House trained, affectionate, intelligent.
Marcus, male Beagle mix born April 2, 2019. House-trained, very vocal, intelligent, energetic.
House and fenced yard only.

These two dogs like to work physically and mentally. Daily activities should therefore be planned (  walks on leash, food search games, mental problems, etc) in order to stimulate them and channel their great energy. Hatfield and Marcus are looking for very active people, very present, with experience of the breed, a non-urban environment without other animals, children or teens.

In the Comments box, please tell us about yourself and why you believe that this dog is a good match for you.  Please include your phone number, your dog experience, whether you live in an apartment or house, members of the household including pets, and whether you have a fenced in yard.  

Please do not call the shelter for information concerning our adoptable animals. Thank you!

Only successful adoption requests will receive a return email or a phone call.

Adoption Fee:  $ 340, including sterilization, vaccination and dewormer.   There are no taxes.

NOTE:  We do not adopt dogs to families with children 10 years of age and under.

animal.description:
Just Wow!  That's the best way to describe Magoo once you meet and experience his steady demeanor.  This guy is "unflappable" and seems that nothing can rattle his steady, level headed personality.  He can be silly and playful too, like his attempts to grab your toes while you walk.  This guy is a mess.  He is so incredibly polite and low key in the house, gets along great with the pack, he just blended right in with the other 8 males on the farm. He exudes a super positive energy and is a delight to handle.  Magoo has excellent recall and never wanders too far from his person.  He is handsome to a fault and has a brilliant coat pattern.  You just cannot order a dog more amazing than Magoo!  He is definitely a keeper so we will be looking for a special forever home for him.  He deserves it!  Send us a text or call at 812-267-2814 for our adoption application.

Our adoption fee is a $180 non-refundable donation which includes:

Spay/Neuter
Rabies Vaccination

6-Way Vaccination
Heartworm Testing and Treatment if necessary
Worming 
Socialization with other dogs 
History of Origin of your new pet, complete medical history and veterinary contacts
Dedicated support after Adoption
Lifelong Safety Net for your Pet
Tips for your individual dog for a successful adoption and transition
   
We do not adopt out any dog as housebroken. Housebreaking your new pet is an important part of the bonding process and is a necessary commitment for a successful transition. Those first few weeks in your  home are when your new dog learns to trust and respect you, as his person. When adopting make sure you have thought out a potty training routine ahead of time, before bringing a new dog into your home.   We do reserve the right to inspect the home to ensure there will not be any conflicts or issues that could result in an unsuccessful introduction to the family.  In addition you may rest assured that every dog  offered to the public for adoption by All American Dawgs has been handled and under direct guidance of our personnel for no less than 30 days.  This time period is necessary to assess each pet, individually, for health issues and individual behavior  before they go to new homes.  Each and every dog, during this period, will get regular exercise via pack walks through the countryside and regular direction in  basic manners while  learning extremely necessary socialization skills.  Our goal is to bridge committed adopters to good minded companions and this is accomplished by helping rescue dogs learn the basic skills necessary for that next step, your family. 

Adopters must meet and spend time with their newly adopted dog via a scheduled Meet and Greet here at All American Dawgs in Rockport, Indiana.  We do not ship our dogs under any circumstances as they are members of our family and their safety is    Priority # 1.

Please visit our FaceBook site at https://www.facebook.com/AADawgs for even more albums and information of our adoptable dogs.  Give us a like and enjoy the updates of our friends and adopters.  The happiness and satisfaction of our adopters is of utmost importance as our adoptive families become part of the A. A. D. family.

If you see a dog that you would like to get to know a little better please email us at: 
AllAmericanDawgs@gmail.com or call at 812-267-2814 to receive an adoption
application to complete.  Once the application has been processed by All American Dawgs (usually within 24-48 hours) we will call you to set up a meet and greet day that is most convenient to your family.

Anyone that wishes to meet a particular dog must complete our application process first.  We do not have an open to the public facility and the best way to reach us is via email  at  AllAmericanDawgs@gmail. com or text at 812-267-2814.  Please also enjoy additional pictures under photos on our FaceBook site  https://www.facebook.com/AADawgs

animal.description:
Last week we got an urgent plea for help for puppies in a terrible situation. Tiny babies outdoors in the cold. 3 were lost when someone went out to look but thankfully were found. All loaded with worms and coccidia. Poor Kipper has a broken leg which will require surgery and little Kina is very small compared to her siblings. Thankfully, we had a foster step up and we were able to get them the medical care they desperately needed. In just a few short days these babies have started to thrive. They are getting rid of those yucky parasites, eating great and learning what the good life of being indoors is all about. We honestly have no idea of the mix of these pups. They are estimated to be 6 weeks old. They are all very tiny. All but Kina weigh 2-3 lbs and little Kina is barely 1 lb. They are playful and developing little personalities. We believe they likely will stay pretty small based on their size now but that’s truly a guess as we have no history on their parents. These babies will not be ready for 3 more weeks. Kina and Kipper possibly longer due to medical issues but that is something we we determine as we go. The earliest pick up date would be 2/10 after their second round of vaccinations, dewormed and they are altered. We will start taking apps on these precious little ones and reserving them to the perfect forever homes. 

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Polly is a 1.5 year old pittie mix, who is 70 lbs of pure love.
She was adopted out as a puppy and has come back to us recently for eating a chicken. So we know chickens aren’t her thing! However, she’s amazing with other dogs and people.  She is loving the walks she’s getting at the Stray Cafe, and especially her newfound friends and all of the attention!  
She’s house and crate trained, spayed, and heartworm negative.  This is definitely one girl you don’t want to miss!  

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
PLEASE answer questions below, we are only compiling potential adopters for her currently. As we are a small team, we are not accepting phone calls for our dogs at this time, you can e-mail us directly with questions answered at shelter@hbpets.org. 

Squash came in as a stray to HBPets. Squash is approx. 2 years old. Squash is a spayed female, Pit Bull/Heeler Mix. Squash is a very sweet, sensitive little girl. She is nervous about people, in a timid way. She doesn't like yelling or really loud noises. Squash has Horners Syndorme to the left side of her face, this has caused a drooping effect, most likely she was born with this syndrome, it doesn't cause her any issues, it doesn't bother her, but does make pictures hard. She would love a quiet family, who would dote on her, make her apart of the family, take her places like the beach, give her time to adjust to her new life. She would prefer children over the age of 12yrs, dogs who are calm like her, shes not to sure about cats. She would like room to run, and no apartments. 

Now that we have listed what she needs in a home, let us tell you about what we see in her!!! Squash is the squishiest, sweetest, intelligent, loving pup. Her 1st 2yrs of life someone loved this dog, she ignores other dogs, she doesn't jump, she loves to run and is a very goofy dog. 

My adoption fee is $250.00

Dog adoption are by appointment only, we will contact you. 

1. Are you a homeowner or renter? 
2. If you are a renter can your provide a letter from your landlord stating you can have a dog? Squash is not an apartment dog. 
3. Do you have a fully, secured fenced yard? 
4. Do you have the time patience to let her adjust to her new surroundings? 
5. Are you active, hiking etc
5. How many people and there ages live in your home? 
6. How many other pets and types? Primary Color: Red Secondary Color: White Weight: 40.8lbs Age: 2yrs 0mths 2wks Animal has been Spayed

Sadie is reserved at first meet and just needs a little time to trust. Once she's comfortable, her true self shines! She needs lots of exercise to keep her mind and body happy! Sadie is working on leash walking manners and is very food motivated. She knows some basic commands and is eager to learn more. Sadie is affectionate and enjoys a good back scratch! 

***Sadie must go to a home with another confident dog(s). She will need to meet any potential canine siblings prior to adoption, to ensure compatibility. Any children in the home must be 16 and older. There cannot be any cats or small animals in the home

Sadie is 3 years old, 56 lbs., spayed and current on vaccinations.

 adoption@popememorialcvhs.org

How To Adopt a Pet

We are currently offering adoptions by appointment only, due to the Coronavirus. The Adoption Center remains closed to drop-in visitors.

The process to schedule an appointment begins with the submission of an application, which can be found on our website. Once the application is approved, we will reach out to you to schedule an appointment. Please bear with us, the new process has slowed our response time.

If you do not see an animal that would fit into your home, we highly recommend checking our website weekly as new animals may become available. We do not offer a waitlist for specific breeds, types, etc. 

As always, adoptions are first come, first serve, meaning the applicant who is approved first gets their choice of available appointment times and thus his/her choice of animals to meet and adopt. We are not able to extend holds on any animals at this time, so we ask interested adopters to make their adoption decision during their appointment and be prepared to take their new pet home with you.

animal.description:
Jack Available for Adoption
Status: Available for Adoption
Activity Level: Companion
Age: 11-14 years old
Gender: Male
Weight: 45 pounds
Color: Black and White
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Housetrained: Yes
Foster Location: Charlotte, North Carolina
Adoption Price: $250.00 
About Jack

Super-sweet Jack was given up by his owner when she had to move into a place where she couldn’t keep him. It was a heartbreaking decision, but this handsome, senior border collie-beagle seems to understand and is ready for his true, forever home.

Jack loves staying close to his people while inside, but is also independent when he’s out searching for new smells in the backyard. He adores going on walks with his two foster sisters. He’s amazing on the leash and is so happy when he gets to stop and smell something new. He’s up for two walks a day and once he gets home, is so proud of himself after his big adventure.

Jack loves people and gets along great with other dogs. He’s very chatty. His hound side comes out when he talks to his people, especially when he’s happy to see them, when it’s time for a walk, or (of course) when it’s time to eat.
This laid-back boy really enjoys family time but won’t turn down a chance to nap. (We feel the same, Jack.)

Jack requires frequent potty breaks during the day and wears a doggy diaper at night. He takes medication for pain to keep him feeling his best.
His perfect home would be a calm family where someone would take him on walks and be around most of the time. He’d like a fenced-in backyard to keep him safe. He needs a home without cats and children, and with a calm, low-energy adult dog.

Jack is being fostered in Charlotte, North Carolina.

Application link-
https://prbcr.org/bor.../border-collie-adoption-application/

PRBCR needs a satisfactory vet reference with records of annual exam, vaccines, heartworm test, and purchase records for your dogs monthly year round heartworm preventatives, and vetting for cats. We adopt to homes in NC, SC, and GA. The adoption fee is $250.00, and the final step of the application for adoption process is the home visit. 

Thank you for your interest in adopting a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Take a look at that attentive little face.  This girlie wants to learn and she has had a very full history of working on the farm.  Little has been around horses, dogs of all sizes and ages.  Her socialization around other dogs is complete.  Little takes regular pack walks with the other rescue dogs, sometimes 8-10 in a group. She knows how to navigate within a group and understands the words "Leave it."  Little has amazing recall and knows basic demands such as "Kennel, back, sit, ah-ah, off, etc"  She learns so so fast which leads me to believe she could make a fun competition dog.  Believe it or not her Momma was a purebred red heeler who came to us with a litter of 7 babies.  This gal is not going to be a  big dog, maybe 40 pounds but she is going to be fun.  Little helps me build brush pile fires and knows the safety necessary, she helps me feed to the horses and she stays close by at all times.  She is very well kenneled trained too.  We are looking for the right person to continue the rest of her story.  Text or call at 812-267-2814 and let us send your our application! 

Our adoption fee is a $180 non-refundable donation which includes:

Spay/Neuter
Rabies Vaccination
Microchip

6-Way Vaccination
Heartworm Testing and Treatment if necessary
Worming 
Socialization with other dogs 
History of Origin of your new pet, complete medical history and veterinary contacts
Dedicated support after Adoption
Lifelong Safety Net for your Pet
Tips for your individual dog for a successful adoption and transition
   
We do not adopt out any dog as housebroken. Housebreaking your new pet is an important part of the bonding process and is a necessary commitment for a successful transition. Those first few weeks in your  home are when your new dog learns to trust and respect you, as his person. When adopting make sure you have thought out a potty training routine ahead of time, before bringing a new dog into your home.   We do reserve the right to inspect the home to ensure there will not be any conflicts or issues that could result in an unsuccessful introduction to the family.  In addition you may rest assured that every dog  offered to the public for adoption by All American Dawgs has been handled and under direct guidance of our personnel for no less than 30 days.  This time period is necessary to assess each pet, individually, for health issues and individual behavior  before they go to new homes.  Each and every dog, during this period, will get regular exercise via pack walks through the countryside and regular direction in  basic manners while  learning extremely necessary socialization skills.  Our goal is to bridge committed adopters to good minded companions and this is accomplished by helping rescue dogs learn the basic skills necessary for that next step, your family. 

Adopters must meet and spend time with their newly adopted dog via a scheduled Meet and Greet here at All American Dawgs in Rockport, Indiana.  We do not ship our dogs under any circumstances as they are members of our family and their safety is    Priority # 1.

Please visit our FaceBook site at https://www.facebook.com/AADawgs for even more albums and information of our adoptable dogs.  Give us a like and enjoy the updates of our friends and adopters.  The happiness and satisfaction of our adopters is of utmost importance as our adoptive families become part of the A. A. D. family.

If you see a dog that you would like to get to know a little better please email us at: 
AllAmericanDawgs@gmail.com or call at 812-267-2814 to receive an adoption
application to complete.  Once the application has been processed by All American Dawgs (usually within 24-48 hours) we will call you to set up a meet and greet day that is most convenient to your family.

Anyone that wishes to meet a particular dog must complete our application process first.  We do not have an open to the public facility and the best way to reach us is via email  at  AllAmericanDawgs@gmail. com or text at 812-267-2814.  Please also enjoy additional pictures under photos on our FaceBook site  https://www.facebook.com/AADawgs

We are head over heels for this handsome boy we call Kookaburra. He is a Heeler/Boxer mix with an estimated birth date of 12/09/2020. He is working on house breaking and kennel training. animal.description:
Bart will melt your heart! This older gentleman adores people and is such a sweet soul. He's a very loving dog who will snuggle up if you sit on the floor with him, and will leave his dog bed to check and see how you are doing. Bart can spend the day lounging around the house, but is very happy to go on a long walk or play with a toy. He is house trained and will whine if it's been too long since he has gone outside. He currently lives with two cats in his foster home and has always been friendly with them, and on walks he usually ignores other dogs or wags his tail when they pass him. Bart can be a little nervous around new people, but usually warms up pretty quickly, especially if they have treats! He is mostly deaf, so he cannot hear commands like sit, but he does respond to touch to get his attention.

*Bart is a part of our Hospice Program because he has been diagnosed with large cell lymphoma, a form of cancer. This sweet old man is looking for a special family who will diligently monitor and provide care for his quality of life and overall comfort for whatever time he has left. He's ready to be spoiled with all the love you have to offer!*

Age: 8 years

How I came to PAWS: Found Stray

Animal ID#: 48996

Weight: 55lbs

Mixed breed (It's impossible to identify breed mix by sight alone, so for most dogs, their mix is only a guess. We get to know each dog as an individual and strive to make matches based on personality, not on breed label.)

Location: Foster Care
All our dog meets are by appointment only; to get started, please complete the adoption application. To learn more about this dog, please contact us at adoptions@phillypaws.org or 215-298-9680 ext. 16._____________________________________
To adopt a cat, complete the application at phillypaws.org/catapp.To adopt a dog, complete the application at phillypaws.org/dogapp.
Please reference this animal's ID NUMBER when inquiring.
Learn more about PAWS' adoption process, locations, and more at: phillypaws.org/adopt/info.
__________________________________________Adoption fees include age-appropriate vaccinations, spay/neuter, and microchip. Adoption fees are as follows, plus tax: $150 for large adult dogs (older than 1 year); $250 for small dogs (under 25 lbs) and all puppies (under 1 year); $60 for adult cats (over 6 months of age), and $100 for kittens (under 6 months of age). When you adopt a pair of kittens together, the total adoption fee is $150.
PAWS, the Philadelphia Animal Welfare Society, is a 501(c)3 non-profit animal rescue organization dedicated to saving Philadelphia's homeless and at-risk animals. PAWS is the city's largest rescue partner and provider of low-cost, basic veterinary care. Through our adoption locations, special events, and network of foster homes, PAWS finds loving homes for thousands of animals every year. PAWS is working to make Philadelphia a no-kill city where every healthy and treatable pet is guaranteed a home. Please visit www.phillypaws.org for more information on adopting, fostering, volunteering, or donating.

animal.description:
Penny is a sturdy, solid dog who likes to be around people. She is 4 years old. A Velcro dog who will follow you around the house, this pooch will lean in for pets and may even give you a smooch. While she has made progress in training, her adopters will need to continue to encourage and guide her on her path to good canine citizenship. Because we are not sure if she gets along with other dogs, to be on the safe side, we recommend that Penny go to a home with no other dogs. Because she can be rather exuberant and may knock a child over, any kids in her home should be 8 or older, dog-savvy, and sturdy.  

Penny’s ideal home is one where someone wants to have a constant companion nearby.  Although she is 56 lbs, she sees herself as a lap dog. And what could be better than a nap in a lap? She adores snuggling on the sofa with people. And she believes in equal opportunity. When her foster family’s sons were home from college, she would wander from person to person throughout the day, spending time with everyone. She loves to be pet or scratched, especially on her rear.  

Indoors, Penny tends to be loving and mostly quiet. Outdoors, she tends to bark at other dogs that get too close or at any dog that first barks at her. When encountering human males, Penny can also be a bit barky. But she has calmed down after a visitor sat down and, in another case,  after she was able to carefully approach a man to check him out.

Penny has been known to counter surf—when no one is looking. But otherwise, she does not chew on things that are not hers. Instead, she enjoys taking her time, savoring a Kong stuffed with something yummy.

Penny sleeps in a crate at night, not making a peep even in the morning as her foster mom gets ready for the day. She doesn’t react at all to the doorbell. She rides well in the car.  And she isn’t food aggressive at all.

Penny has mastered sit and touch. Sometimes she’ll offer a sit and look up to you for her reward—before you’ve even asked. She knows her name. And sometimes she knows stay. On the leash, she may pull, but overall is quite good. With an adopter’s commitment and support, she can continue to make progress on loose leash walking with a front-clip harness.  Penny's adopter will need to be committed to positive, force-free training to work on dog-dog interactions, loose leash walking, and other basic manners.

Penny used to always want to meet people as if they were dogs. She would leap to try to lick your muzzle. But in recent weeks, she has managed to curb the urge and resort to calmer, politer greetings. Now, after being left alone a while, upon her foster mom’s return, Penny will jump up, bouncy and excited, so happy to see her. But after a quick walk, she usually is back to her normal, quiet self. Penny is perfectly content to stay in her dog bed under a desk all day long as her foster mom works. Every few hours, she will stand up to get pet or to lick a hand. Then she settles back down.

Penny’s needs are simple: the company of a friendly human, a warm place to sleep, food, and a few walks. In return, she will reward a lucky family with a lifetime of snuggles and joy.

If you are interested in any of our rescues, please fill out our non-binding application which can be found here - www.hedgesvillehounds.com (or https://hedgesvillehounds.wixsite.com/home).  You will need to copy and paste the URL into your browser.  You may also contact us using the "Contact this Organization" button above.

animal.description:
Hope will never lose her sense of wonder and she's ready for that dance of life. If interested in adopting Hope please fill out an application here http://www.bestfriendsforlifeanimalrescue.com/                                                                                                                                                         I hope you never lose your sense of wonder You get your fill to eat but always keep that hunger Give the Heavens above more than just a passing glance And when you get the choice to sit it out or dance I hope you dance. - from 'I Hope You Dance' by Lee Ann Womack
Hope is an adorable little 3 month old Lab mix currently weighing around 15 lbs and will likely be a medium sized girl up to 50 lbs when full grown. She is a sweet smart baby who is learning all kinds of new things. She's working on her house and crate training along with some basic commands. Hope is a social little girl who likes to be around her people to see what's going on. She gets along with everyone she meets and does well with other dogs. Hope is already spayed, up to date on all vaccinations, current on preventatives, and micro chipped. She's ready to find her forever loving family and home who will always love her sense of wonder. Be sure to give this sweet girl more than a passing glance, don't sit this one out cuz Hope is looking forward to the dance.

animal.description:
Sweet Otto, recent HOPE Fund recipient now ready for adoption or foster!

10-year-old Shepherd Mix Otto, unfortunately, hasn't had it easy up to this point. After facing years of neglect and in need of urgent medical care upon arrival at the Norfolk SPCA, he's finally ready to find a home to give him ALL the love he deserves.
Otto is a friendly dog who may need a more extended adjustment period to get used to his new home inside, as he has spent his whole life outside. He was never given a chance to be a family member. Otto hangs on every word and eagerly offers his head and side for attention. Otto's a true lap dog!

He is looking for a family that will support him as he heals from his hernia repair surgery and learns the ins-and-outs of indoor manners and basic training. He is like a puppy and will need a regular and consistent potty schedule. 
Otto's ideal household would have older kids, and Otto wouldn't mind a dog or feline pal!

animal.description:
Bubba is Bulldog mix, around 4 years old and 50 pounds. 
Bubba was found dumped along with his sister at 6 months old at someone’s home. Although a kind samaritan began looking for rescue, years passed and nothing came of it. This left Bubba and Sista to stay outdoors at their home on tethers, then in kennels. 
Bubba is a sweet, lovable boy. He’d do best as the only dog in the home. Bubba is high heartworm positive and is undergoing treatment. Bubba deserves a home like any dog does. Be his light!

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
Only applications for adoption in Durham Region will be considered.  Any out of area applications will be disregarded.  Please see our website for information on our adoption process.

Benji came to TAGS from a local shelter where he was surrendered.  He was having a very difficult time in that environment so the shelter contacted us – understandable as that can be a very stressful place for a dog!  He is a 3-year-old Beagle, approximately 45 pounds and currently not neutered (TAGS will arrange for neutering when the clinic reopens – currently closed due to COVID).  He was very stressed, and the move to his foster home has revealed a very affectionate boy who follows his foster everywhere she goes.  He has come out of his shell and made great strides in his new environment in a matter of weeks. 
 
Benji is housetrained.  He sleeps in his crate at night in his foster’s bedroom and settles quickly.  However, when you put him in his crate during the day and leave him (even for another room), he makes it know that he is not impressed – queue the howling that hounds are so well known for.  He needs to be put in his crate when opening the front door as he has a naughty habit of trying to dash out.   
 
When Benji sees a person or dog outside he does howl and bark.  He pulls on his leash but this has improved in the short time he has been with his foster.  He is also getting better with his recall, coming when called about 50% of the time.  
 
Benji is looking for a where his adopters are active and committed to taking him out for several walks a day as he has lots of energy to burn.  He loves running after balls and is very fast!  Experience with the breed or hounds in general is an asset.  Someone who is at home part or most of the day would be ideal given he does currently show some separation anxiety.   
 
Because he can get overstimulated – he is still young afterall! - Benji would do best in a home with no children or other animals.  As he is vocal, an apartment or condo would not be a good place for Benji.  A fenced yard is a must as in typical Beagle fashion, Benji follows his nose and will dig to try and keep on the scent.   
 
We suspect Benji wasn’t properly socialized in his past life, so he is a bit of a nervous nelly.  He needs a structured home where his new family will continue to work on building his confidence.  He has all the ingredients to make a wonderful family member and in the words of his foster, is a real sweetheart.

animal.description: My name is Taiki and I'm looking for my forever home. I'm 7 years old and I'm a big boy at 38 pounds! Foster mom calls me her Gentle Giant and says that I'm a really good boy! I've only been living here for a few weeks. I came from a commercial breeding facility, so living in a home with people is a whole new world for me, but I'm getting used to it. I love to run around and play in the fenced back yard here at my foster home. I like to follow foster mom around, wagging my tail and asking her to play with me. When I'm inside, I am calm, well-mannered, and still a bit cautious and timid. I'm not a barker and have been a good boy when left alone. I'm not sure yet what to do with toys and right now I'm not really food motivated. My favorite thing to do inside is when foster mom pets me and I will approach her when I want some lovin'. I'm healthy and I'm very good with other dogs, but I haven't met any small kids yet. Sometimes new things or loud noises spook me, but in the end, my curiosity wins and I come back to investigate. My ideal forever home would have a fenced in yard where I can play,  and another friendly well-mannered dog for me to learn from, but these aren't required. If you don't have a securely fenced yard, just know that I will need some patience with additional leash training because I get really excited sometimes and pull hard. I'm being fostered in Adrian, Michigan. If you live in the midwest and are interested in a Gentle Giant like me, visit www.savingshibas.com/adopt to start the process of becoming approved to adopt from SIRA.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting Josie, please email kat.sanders@lostdogrescue.org

 'Toot toot, the energy train is here and Josie is your driver!'

If you need some morning motivation, this girl has it in spades and then some. Josie is at her happiest when she is racing and wrestling with a doggy friend so if you have a high energy, sturdy framed playmate at home that you struggle to tire out, look no further, Josie will do the job for you.

She is smart and easily steered with verbal cues, she is practicing "sit" and "down" with lots of her favorite treats to keep her focused. She sleeps nicely in a crate through the night and will trade toys for treats. 

Josie would thrive in an active home with a yard and a resident dog to play with. She needs a committed owner who is as motivated as she is to get out and log those steps. Josie has done well around children but would do best in a home with older human siblings or adults as she not always as spatially aware as she could be and could easily knock over little ones!

She would also make an excellent running companion or thrill seeking best friend, ready to join you on any adventure! 

Contact the email above to find out how you can meet Josie!

Estimated DOB: 9/11/2017

Sponsored by Brian McNeill

Ziggy is your typical young male mastiff. Goofy, playful, unaware of his size and power. Would easily knock a child or average adult (for that matter) over without realizing it. He LOVES other dogs and is very respectful. and takes correction well. He is a slobbery boy and can drink a bowl of water in a minute with half of it ending up on the floor. Leash manners are a work in progress but he is crate trained and house broken.
He will do best in a home with breed experience, no small children that could get forcefully knocked over, nor children that would be bringing a lot of kids into the home, a fenced yard and another dog to play with. It is imperative that he be exercised regularly to burn his energy. Ziggy is an all around AWESOME dog.


Apply today at www.realrottweilerrescue.com 

Please note: The prospective owner must agree to a screening process that includes an application and the signing of an adoption contract.

Our goal is to find the best match for our dogs and their new families, so that everyone lives happily ever after.

We prefer homes who want to go to an obedience class. Training strengthens the bond and trust that you have with your dog, and it's fun, for both of you! Dogs like to think and to be mentally challenged. The training you do together will be an investment in the future. 

We will try to respond within 24-48 hours, but please be patient as we are volunteer based. We all have full time jobs and are busy with other rescue matters.

Thank you!

animal.description: Introducing Chickie! She is a 7 year old Jack Russell Terrier/Dachshund mix (perhaps with some Chihuahua mixed in there for good measure!) and weighs 13lbs. Chickie came from her lifelong home where she lived with her parents and 5 siblings. She was extremely closely bonded to a sister, but was unfortunately separated from her after one of her owners passed away. Chickie has been learning to find her way without her partner in crime, but it has been a very tough journey, as she relied on her canine friend for her confidence. She came to us panicked, under-socialized, and terrified of even her own shadow. With patience and consistent handling, Chickie has slowly been gaining confidence and has been learning that the world is not a scary place. Chickie is just learning how to walk on a leash, but is finding that sniffing and exploring can be fun! She is also making progress on her housetraining. Chickie will need adopters experienced with fearful dogs - she is a project, but with time and patience, she will blossom into an amazing canine companion! Chickie's future home must have a securely fenced yard - she is an extremely skittish girl and is a flight risk. Chickie would love to be your one and only or pending introductions, she may do well sharing a home with a calm, confident dog to help show her the ropes. Due to her skittish nature, Chickie will need a quiet, adult-only home. Connecticut adopters preferred. To learn how to make Chickie your next 4-legged family member, please contact Michelle at michelle.p@poainc.org.

Meet Adele! This girl is 3 years old and 55 lbs. She is a little shy but she has a gentle spirit about her and is eager to show affection. She knows how to sit on command and is potty and crate trained. Adele would love a playmate to keep her company and bring out her silly side, but she also rocks the solo pup life. If you’re looking for a gentle pittie to welcome into your world, look no further! Adele is a sweet pup and will be a wonderful addition to a family looking for an affectionate, easy-going buddy.

animal.description:
Axel is a handsome red doberman pinscher that was born on June 18 2020.  He is smart, playful and affectionate.  He weighed 64 lbs on January 28th and is still a growing boy estimated to be around 90 lbs full grown.  He loves walks, hikes and daily exercise.  He is a BIG PUPPY that needs daily stimulation and exercise.  He has a sensitive stomach so he needs to be fed special food.  He is currently being fed Purina Pro Plan Salmon and Rice for Sensitive Stomach's.  He can be a little shy at first but once he gets to know you he will give you kisses and more kisses.  He know sit, shake, down, speak and stay.  He would not be good in a home with small dogs because he if a bit of a rough player and plays too rough with a small dog, however, he is good with cats.  He will require basic obedience, continued crate training, house and leash training.  He would do well with a gentle lead leash as he tends to pull and he is a super strong puppy!  He likes to be the dominate one with dogs and sometimes humans so it's very important learns YOU are the dominate one. He is sweet and goofy and will make a GREAT pet for the right home that understands the breed.  Please be descriptive in your application on why you feel Axel would be a good match for your home.

Adoption fees details: 
Puppies - Adults $ 550, Seniors $375. These adoption rates include transport from Alexandria, Louisiana to designated New England adopter pick up locations and NE foster homes using either Rescue Road Trips, Pets LLC or CAFA Transport. If you do a search you will see that this is a very reasonable adoption fee and comparable to other rescues. Adoption fee breakdown:Adoption Fee:   $  365.00Transportation Fee:  $ 185.00MA and NH only--Quarantine fee if applicable:  $125.00

Medical details:
All our dogs are altered (spayed or neutered), DHLPP, rabies, Bordetella, Heartworm tested with negative test results, microchipped, treated for parasites and on monthly heartworm and flea and tick prevention. A health certificate is issued by a licensed Louisiana veterinarian.

Adoption details:  
In some instances, a meet and greet is not possible before adoption unless we have a foster home in New England available. Available for a Meeting confirms the dog is in a NE Foster home and available for a meeting in the city state provided.  Most times our dogs get adopted before a foster home becomes available - and if so, they go straight to adopters home. Foster parents talk to adopters and feel confident that this will be a match before our dogs are transported up. Also if by some chance it is not a match we have a safety net in place as we ask that adopters to let us know that it is not a match and we direct you to take the dog to a foster home or boarding kennel once that is arranged. If necessary, we will ask you to foster the dog until a foster home can be arranged. 
Transport details:Rescue Road Trips (rescueroadtrips.com), Pets LLC (petsllc.net) or CAFA Transport will deliver our precious pups on commercial rescue animal transport to designated locations.  The fee is 185.00 which IS INCLUDED in your adoption fee already.**Rescue Road Trips, was featured on The Today Show - view it at http://www.today.com/video/today/55034556#55034556

MA and NH RESIDENTS:
If you are a Massachusetts or New Hampshire residence, an additional fee of $125.00 will apply due to State quarantine fee requirements. If the dog is in a foster home in MA or NH, this fee will be added in the adoption fee regardless of where the adopters home is located making the total adoption fee $675.00 for puppies and adults $500.00 for Seniors, otherwise the full adoption fee for all other states is $550.00 for puppies and adults and $375.00 for seniors. This includes a 48 quarantine, recheck by a MA licensed veterinarian, and issued a MA health certificate.

Visit all our available dogs at www.cenlaallianceforanimals.comWe update and add dogs frequently.

We hope to help make a difference in a rescue dogs life into loving responsible homes.

animal.description:
Name: Montegue
Age: ~2 Years
Breed: Staffy-Pitt mix
Size(full grown): Medium (~55 pounds) 
Adoption Fee: $400

About Montegue:
Montegue is a medium energy dog. He enjoys playing but also enjoys a relaxing evening. He loves toys and eating bully sticks. A kennel environment really stresses him out and it makes us hard to judge what his personality is really like. He can be around other dogs, but he can be a bit too high energy for a lot of dogs. He doesn't take corrections well from other dogs. He would do best in a home as the only pet or in a home with a very submissive and playful dog. Once trained and taught proper manners, we think his friendliness with dogs will improve. He wants to play nicely, but he doesn't know how. He is looking for an owner that is willing to help him with this. He is very smart and will learn fast. He enjoys long walks that end in some couch snuggles. He hasn't been destructive at all and his house training is going well. He has been through a lot and he just needs someone that will give him a chance. He has some fur loss from demodex, but it has been treated and is growing back. He is a super loving boy that will steal your heart if you give him a chance.

Apply for this pup here: swww.whenthegoinggetsruff.org/adopt

animal.description:
Howdy! My name is Jack; foster Mom calls me ""Jack The Lad"". I am a little over a year old and we think I am an Australian Shepherd/Blue Heeler mix. As you can see I am a very handsome young guy. I am good with other dogs, I can play for hours. Mom says I need an active family, I would agree with that; I need to be kept busy or I may get into trouble ;)
I am a happy guy that loves to play out in the back yard. After the initial excitement of going fro a walk I am great on the leash.

Life is good for me now and I am very happy: it wasn't always like that. I was found wandering a neighborhood emaciated, I was hungry and very thirsty. So thirsty that I became fascinated with drinking water, I put my foster family through some very worrying times. I would drink gallons of water and then i needed to get up 2-3 times in the middle of the night to go potty. Everyone is glad that's in the past. We were all sleep deprived, my rescue held nothing back on getting me help, I had lots of tests done and even stayed at the Vet office for a whole day, that was fun!! Those Vet techs are fun girls :)

Anyway, nothing abnormal could be found and the Dr lady said it was all in my head; she called it a fancy name (polydipsia)

Through support and a lot of love from my foster Mom and Dad, I finally feel safe and loved. I still like to drink water but when it's limited amounts I do great. My temperament is typical of my breed; Active, Energetic, Active, Friendly, Active, Alert, Active and Protective.

If you are looking to get plenty exercise send a message to my rescue and my foster Mum will get back to you.Interested in adopting a companion dog or cat from Texas Animal Society?
Please email info@texasanimalsociety.com and complete online adoption application at texasanimalsociety.org
Come visit our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/www.texasanimalsociety.org/

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

One of Holly's puppies (See Holly's bio for more info) Totally guessing on breed, could have some shepherd, husky or Canaan dog too besides other breeds.
Very sweet female pup. Approximately 5 or 5.5 months old (Estimate).

Ivy maybe from a previous litter, she seems a bit older than the other 3 pups that were with Mom Holly in the pound, but they call came into the pound together. (Maybe Ivy has a different Mom altogether and just ended up with Holly and her other 3 puppies- we are not sure)

Ivy is very bonded to Holly and loves to be with her, but also loves being with the 15 year old in the foster home. Ivy will need another dog in the household to help give her psychological confidence and put her at ease.

Ivy did come into rescue with an injury metacarpal fracture in her front left leg. She has a splint on her leg to help it heal and needs bandage changes for 6 weeks at one of our vets in Edina and then we'll check the injury again (Basically the rescue will see her through this). Ivy is under socialized like her mom Holly but will break your heart with her sweet sensitivity. Ivy likes to sleep with the 15 year old in her foster home and really wants to bond and trust. Ivy must go to a home with another dog as she will need this to boost her confidence. Ideal home would be fenced in yard, another dog, maybe some older kids. She loves kids.
fracture!!

https://redemptionroadrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=4003
.

PLEASE NOTE: We expect a high volume of interest in this puppy, so please be patient with us as we review all applications. As a foster-based rescue, we don't have a facility for visits with multiple animals. Meet & greets with dogs are arranged one the pre-adoption application has been received, processed, reviewed, AND approved.

For Puppies adoption fee is $450.00 for the age appropriate vetting they have had so far. (2 DHPP vaccines, deworming on a schedule, and will come with microchip) Puppies still need: 1-2 more DHPP vaccines and a rabies on an age appropriate schedule, and eventual spay or neuter (recommended when closer to 5 1/2- 6 months old) If you want the puppy altered with our vet, the adoption fee is $650.00 (adopter is responsible for the in between vaccines). If you want to alter (spay or neuter) your puppy at your vet, the adoption fee is $450.00, and we ask you to sign a spay/neuter contract and will need to show proof of S/N at later date.
